metadata.name: SoulSea #238
metadata.description:
The Soul Sea

You look down and find that the ocean in your heart is a sine wave. 
The tide gently laps onto the shore.

The soul is the sea. You are the land. 
There are waves on the shore, and the waves are slices.

Gazing at the slices, you feel the coldness of the Arctic Ocean, the permafrost of the Antarctic Sea, the deep darkness of the bottomless sea.

Stay silent, hear the sound of the waves lapping at the innumerable shores far away.
Feel the soul of the digital ocean.

Interactivities:
> Key P: Pause
> Key S: Save
> Press and move mouseX: wave moves slower / faster

Che-Yu Wu

metadata.name: Primodial Spiral #3
metadata.description:
Initially, I wrote some code to create rotating polygons to test my pen plotter. Then I realized that the motion of the polygons was interesting, so I connected the polygon vertices to try to visualize this motion.  The result was some interesting curves that varied with the number of polygons and vertices. 

The most interesting thing to me was the large number of different outputs that could be made from this simple process. There were many times during development when I got an output that was substantially different from what I had seen prior, even after thousands of iterations.  

Press s to save as an SVG.

Also, I highly recommend using a pen plotter to print out your primordial spiral.

metadata.name: Returns #94
metadata.description:
Returns is an offline-first PWA and an interactive SVG. It combines the joy of interaction, digital color and minimalist sculpture with the potential of a long running, continuously unique visual. Based on “Shipping” from 2016, it is inspired by Anne Truitt, Ugo Rondinone, Imi Knoebel, Kelly Ellsworth and many others.

A subdivision slices the viewport influenced by width, height and depth. Corners are cut by replacing them with two new points, pulled towards each other along the edges. Shapes are “rounded" by repeating this step, keeping the new points close together. As colors change, so do the relations between shapes, even if geometry changes at a slower pace. New compositions are created on click or after a timeout. This progress over time allows for infinite iterations within the space of each token. It is the promise of a seeded starting point, plus the potential for unlimited new and unique iterations and states over time.

metadata.name: Rondelle, Listen #131
metadata.description:
Tap to start sound. Tap to mute.

Inspired by the glass rondelles which hung from the windowsill in my childhood home. I ask myself what would these rondelles sound like if they reflected sound instead of light? To me, I hear hopeful harmonies of memories past, but they are falling in and out of tune and they are occluded by the muffled noise of time.

When a rondelle is minted, a transaction hash is injected into its code. All colors, patterns, sounds, and motions are generated deterministically from this transaction hash.

As the rondelle loads in your browser, a real-time generative algorithm writes tones, noise, feedback, and distortion to three looping audio buffers. During playback, oscillations in pan, pitch, and volume track the visual oscillations among the rondelle's color rings.

Rarity features are included. The least common rondelles are closed center, monochrome, smol, split color, and square.

Made with Web Audio and p5js. Minted on fxhash beta. Idlebit, 2021.

metadata.name: Urban Flora #206
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Mind scribbles #12
monogrid 1.1 CE #197
metadata.description:
Each monogrid artwork gets initialized with a start up algorithm that builds up a set of rectangles and fills them with pixels. There are two different styles, 'Pixel' and 'Line', to create the initial image.

There is a set of 16 animations at work. 4 noise based animations, 4 shifting animations, 4 modulo based animation and 4 reset animations, all run in parallel. Each animation selects a rectangle from the initial setup and edits the pixels in this area. The selection process runs independently and animations can overlap which results in a new style of animation.

monogrid 1.1 is based on the original series at https://monogrid.xyz, but there are no black/white versions included. The color palette is a mixture of one of 12 colors plus black or white.
The fragment shader has been updated in the way the 16 different animations get summed up. This version would appear more chaotic and organic.

monogrid 1.1 - Collectors Edition
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Cables and Clouds #198
metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette
Key 'd' to toggle a special color mode to highlight the different components (and have the number of points used in your specific drawing).

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: sistemas.15 #36
SWTBD - London Prototype #100
metadata.description:
Several ways to break down - London Prototype is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022

A generative geometry systems exploring broken things by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut

mouse:

click: toggle active mode. In active mode, a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features is generated every 10s.

keyboard:

'a' or 'A' : add a slice or point, depending on mode
's' or 'S' : add a slice, regardless of mode
'c' or 'C' : cut mesh along view
'e': decrease explosion factor
'E': increase explosion factor
'r' or 'R': create a new iteration with the same starting geometry and identical features
'v' or 'V': switch view
   '1': Render view
   '2': Point/ plane view
   '3': Slice view
   '4': Construction view
   '5': Mesh view

'+' and '-': zoom in and out
arrow keys: rotate around and translate along the vertical axis
